1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:07,225
When a man delights to read or hear tell about God, that comes of divine grace and is lordly entertainment for the soul.

2
00:00:07,175 --> 00:00:19,337
To entertain God in one’s thoughts is sweeter than honey, but to be sensible of God is teeming consolation to the noble soul, and union with God in love is everlasting joy which we relish here as we are fitted for it.

3
00:00:19,337 --> 00:00:23,762
They are all too few who are fully ripe for gazing in God’s magic mirror.

4
00:00:23,762 --> 00:00:28,687
Precious few succeed in living the contemplative life at all here upon earth.

5
00:00:28,687 --> 00:00:31,825
Many begin, but fail to consummate it.

6
00:00:31,825 --> 00:00:35,000
Because they have not rightly lived the life of Martha.

7
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:41,300
As the eagle spurns its young that cannot gaze at the sun, even so fares it with the spiritual child.

8
00:00:41,300 --> 00:00:45,262
He who would build high must lay firm and strong foundations.

9
00:00:45,262 --> 00:00:53,750
The true foundation is the very way and pattern of our Lord Jesus Christ, who himself declared: ‘I am the way, the truth and the life.

10
00:00:53,750 --> 00:01:03,637
Dionysius says, ‘The soul shall follow God into the desert of his Godhead, so far as here the body follows Christ in outward willing poverty;’—‘But that soul is idle.

11
00:01:03,637 --> 00:01:11,075
To which St Bernard answers: ‘Waiting upon God is not idleness but work which beats all other work to one unskilled in it.

12
00:01:11,075 --> 00:01:14,900
In order to find God, we must seek him in his Godhead.

13
00:01:14,900 --> 00:01:21,737
Christ says, ‘If father and mother or anything else be a hindrance, quit them for good and serve God unhindered.

14
00:01:21,737 --> 00:01:33,500
The philosopher says, ‘The soul which is moved by the power of the Prime Cause need seek no counsel from any human wisdom; he is obeying what transcends wisdom, for he is moved by the latent primitive truth.

15
00:01:33,500 --> 00:01:41,750
Though we meditate upon the blessed works of our Lord’s poverty and his humility, yet coveting them not ourselves, the houghts are useless.

16
00:01:41,750 --> 00:01:46,975
And to covet them is useless too, unless we diligently seek how we may acquire them.

17
00:01:46,975 --> 00:01:50,312
We would fain be humble; but not despised.

18
00:01:50,312 --> 00:01:54,225
To be despised and rejected is the heritage of virtue.

19
00:01:54,225 --> 00:01:57,425
We would be poor too, but without privation.

20
00:01:57,425 --> 00:02:02,275
And doubtless we are patient, except with hardships and with disagreeables.

21
00:02:02,275 --> 00:02:04,475
And so with all the virtues.

22
00:02:04,475 --> 00:02:09,875
The willing poor, unsolaced by corruptibles, descend into the valley of humility.

23
00:02:09,875 --> 00:02:14,775
They are pursued by insult and adversity, the best school of self-knowledge.

24
00:02:14,775 --> 00:02:17,300
And self-knowledge gets God-knowledge.

25
00:02:17,300 --> 00:02:25,612
My children, ye who suffer insult, if the world reject you, do ye therewith likewise assail yourselves, helping to reject yourselves.

26
00:02:25,612 --> 00:02:30,137
Our Lord Jesus Christ said, ‘The servant is not greater than his lord.

27
00:02:30,137 --> 00:02:34,287
If the world hate you, know ye it hated me before it hated you.

28
00:02:34,287 --> 00:02:37,775
We ought to recompense our Lord for all that he has done.

29
00:02:37,775 --> 00:02:42,137
There are plenty to follow our Lord half-way, but not the other half.

30
00:02:42,137 --> 00:02:48,537
They will give up possessions, friends and honours, but it touches them too closely to disown themselves.

31
00:02:48,537 --> 00:02:55,200
Some there be, neither wanting nor looking for honours, yet, chancing to come their way, honours affect them.

32
00:02:55,200 --> 00:03:08,525
St Bernard says: ‘When a soul comes to wanting what few desire: to be nameless, outcast and disgraced, and makes all welcome equally, then she attains to peace and the true freedom needed for real vision in the mirror of divinity.

33
00:03:08,525 --> 00:03:11,937
Perfect rest is absolute freedom from motion.

34
00:03:11,937 --> 00:03:16,550
Our Lord says, ‘Continue in my word and the truth shall make you free.

35
00:03:16,550 --> 00:03:24,212
Freedom of soul consists in this: in finding in herself no sin; in tolerating in herself no spiritual imperfection.

36
00:03:24,212 --> 00:03:28,737
She is more free lacking all hold on what possesses name and it on her.

37
00:03:28,737 --> 00:03:37,012
Freest of all when she transcends her selfhood and flows with all she is into the bottomless abyss of her primordial mould, into God himself.

38
00:03:37,012 --> 00:03:42,262
Our Lord Jesus Christ exhorts us to renounce all things that we may be less hindered.

39
00:03:42,262 --> 00:03:48,550
St Bernard declares: ‘All the time thou occupiest not with God is accounted unto thee for lost.

40
00:03:48,550 --> 00:03:55,212
And again, ‘The most subtle temptation that can beset us is to occupy ourselves too much in outward works.

41
00:03:55,212 --> 00:04:00,987
Further he says, ‘The best preparation I know for heaven is having no home among externals.

42
00:04:01,156 --> 00:04:10,306
Our least interior act is higher and nobler than our grandest outward one, and yet our loftiest interior act halts in God’s unveiled presence in the soul.

43
00:04:10,256 --> 00:04:17,056
The very best work that we can do is to prepare for union with the present God and wait for this with a fixed intention.

44
00:04:17,056 --> 00:04:21,181
St Paul says, Optimum esse unire deo: Best of all is to be one with God.

45
00:04:21,181 --> 00:04:27,406
In this union the soul is dead, not only to all outward but also to all inward ghostly acts.

46
00:04:27,406 --> 00:04:37,093
God operates unhindered, and the soul bears his godly operation to which she yields obediently enough for God to bring to birth his only Son in her no less than in himself.

47
00:04:37,093 --> 00:04:45,343
This is the atonement wherein, in the twinkling of an eye, the soul is made more one with God than by her doing any act, bodily or ghostly.

48
00:04:45,343 --> 00:04:50,181
The oftener this birth happens in the soul the closer grows her union with God.

49
00:04:50,181 --> 00:04:57,468
God is born in the empty soul by discovering himself to her in a new guise without guise, without light in divine light.

50
00:04:57,468 --> 00:05:05,531
St Augustine says, ‘The soul being aflame with divine love, God is born in the soul, the Holy Ghost being the enkindler of love.

51
00:05:05,531 --> 00:05:10,756
God has vouchsafed divine light to the soul that he may blithely work in his own image.

52
00:05:10,756 --> 00:05:14,068
Now no creature can do what is not in its power.

53
00:05:14,068 --> 00:05:22,006
Hence the soul cannot act above herself, not even with the bridal gift that God has given her in the shape of her most exalted faculty.

54
00:05:22,006 --> 00:05:25,706
This light, albeit divine, is still created.

55
00:05:25,706 --> 00:05:28,556
The creator is one and the light another.

56
00:05:28,556 --> 00:05:36,081
So God comes to the soul in love, purposing that love shall raise her to a higher power, to a function superior to her own.

57
00:05:36,081 --> 00:05:39,831
But love fails to tell unless she meets or makes her match.

58
00:05:39,831 --> 00:05:44,981
As far as God finds his likeness in the soul, so far is God in operation.

59
00:05:44,981 --> 00:05:48,706
If her love is boundless, God acts as boundless love.

60
00:05:48,706 --> 00:05:55,706
A man might live a thousand years and go on growing all the time in love, just as fire will burn so long as there is wood.

61
00:05:55,706 --> 00:06:00,143
The bigger the fire and the stronger the wind, the more fiercely it burns.

62
00:06:00,143 --> 00:06:10,368
Now put love for the fire and the Holy Ghost for the wind: the greater the love and the stronger the inspiration of the Holy Ghost in grace, the quicker the work of perfection is achieved.

63
00:06:10,368 --> 00:06:14,206
Yet not suddenly, but by the gradual growth of the soul.

64
00:06:14,206 --> 00:06:18,131
It would not be well for the whole man to be consumed at once.

65
00:06:18,131 --> 00:06:25,131
The soul becomes so one with God that grace confines her; she is not satisfied with grace, for grace is creaturely.

66
00:06:25,131 --> 00:06:33,793
The soul is so curiously glamoured, she does not realise that she exists: she fancies herself God, so utterly she has escaped from self.

67
00:06:33,793 --> 00:06:38,256
But be she never so far gone from self, she goes on being creature.

68
00:06:38,256 --> 00:06:42,431
Pouring a drop of water into a vat of wine does not destroy it.

69
00:06:42,431 --> 00:06:51,731
Seeing herself the soul sees spirit; seeing the angels she again sees spirit; but God is such pure spirit that soul and angel are nigh bodily compared with him.

70
00:06:51,731 --> 00:07:00,093
A portrait of the highest seraph limned in black would be a better likeness far than God portrayed as highest seraph: that were a pre-eminent unlikeness.

71
00:07:00,244 --> 00:07:05,431
Now in the contemplative state we are consumed by fiery love in the Holy Ghost.

72
00:07:05,381 --> 00:07:12,131
Sooner than knowingly commit a sin, venial or mortal, we shall prefer to suffer every imaginable martyrdom.

73
00:07:12,131 --> 00:07:18,606
If by one venial sin we were enabled to release from hell souls without number, we would not ransom them.

74
00:07:18,606 --> 00:07:23,494
Such love to God must a man have to be familiar with him in contemplation.

75
00:07:23,494 --> 00:07:30,419
Moreover, he must have a mind at ease; and in preparing for it, an undisturbed retired spot is necessary.

76
00:07:30,419 --> 00:07:37,231
The body should be rested from bodily labour, not only of the hands but of the tongue as well and all five senses.

77
00:07:37,231 --> 00:07:43,206
The soul keeps clear best in the quiet, but in jaded body is often overpowered by inertia.

78
00:07:43,206 --> 00:07:56,594
Then by strenuous effort we travail in divine love for intellectual vision till, clearing a way through recollected senses, we rise past our own mind to the wonderful wisdom of God, though this is quite beyond the grasp of any creature.

79
00:07:56,594 --> 00:07:58,806
We rise to divine heights.

80
00:07:58,806 --> 00:08:03,581
David says: Accedat homo ad cor altum et exaltabitur deus, that is, Man rising to the summit of his mind is exalted God.

81
00:08:03,581 --> 00:08:08,494
From this divine eminence we see the lowness and insignificance of creatures.

82
00:08:08,494 --> 00:08:21,956
We feel an inkling of the perfection and stability of eternity, for there is neither time nor space, neither before nor after, but everything present in one new, fresh-springing now where millenniums last no longer than the twinkling of an eye.

83
00:08:21,956 --> 00:08:26,631
And we win participation in the manifold delights of the heavenly host.

84
00:08:26,631 --> 00:08:35,819
So great the joy of Mary Queen in heaven, that having but a thousandth part of it, each member of the heavenly company would taste far more than ever they have earned.

85
00:08:35,819 --> 00:08:41,356
There every spirit rejoices in the joy of every other, relishing it each in his degree.

86
00:08:41,356 --> 00:08:49,069
Every celestial inhabitant is, knows and loves in God, in his own self and in every other spirit whether soul or angel.

87
00:08:49,069 --> 00:08:58,769
And the distinctive consciousness of one God in three Persons and the Three one God gives such ineffable, amazing satisfaction that all their passionate longing is fulfilled.

88
00:08:58,769 --> 00:09:09,831
And just what they are full of they crave unceasingly, and what they crave is all their own in new, fresh-springing joyful ecstasy, theirs to enjoy in all security from everlasting unto everlasting.

89
00:09:09,831 --> 00:09:16,506
Thereafter we press on into the truth, into the simplicity God is himself, not seeking what is his.

90
00:09:16,506 --> 00:09:19,119
So we fall into peculiar wonder.

91
00:09:19,119 --> 00:09:23,756
In this wonder let us remain, for human wit is powerless to fathom it.

92
00:09:23,756 --> 00:09:27,869
Plumbing the deeps of divine wonder but stirs facile doubt.
